  "opinion": "As a former student of engineering who experienced the pressure of being a non-STEM major in a field dominated by peers who seemed to share my background, I've observed how stereotype threat can quietly undermine potential. Stereotype threat isn't just a psychological concept—it's the anxiety that arises when individuals feel their group identity might be judged negatively in a situation where they're expected to perform. For example, in my own experience, during a university project where I was one of the few women in a group of engineering students, the constant underestimation of my capabilities by peers, even when I was performing well, created a self-fulfilling prophecy that I wasn't as capable as others. This isn't just about individual performance—it's about systemic issues that can persist even in environments where diversity is promoted. I believe addressing stereotype threat requires more than just awareness; it demands concrete, actionable steps that are integrated into educational and workplace cultures. For instance, mentorship programs that pair students from underrepresented groups with successful professionals in STEM can build confidence and provide role models. Additionally, creating inclusive classrooms where all students feel their contributions are valued can mitigate the negative effects of stereotype threat. It's important to acknowledge that change takes time and patience, but the benefits of fostering an environment where everyone feels they belong and can thrive are worth the effort.",
